      xsi:schemaLocation="Unit file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Unit.xsd">
   <titles>
      <title>Visualizing <math>
            <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
         </math>
      </title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <para>
         <para.body>If <math>
               <latex>n</latex>
            </math> is one of the integers <math>
               <latex>1,2,3</latex>
            </math>, then we may visualize <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math> as follows</para.body>
      </para>
      <para>
         <para.body>
            <strong>Visualizing</strong>
            <math>
               <latex>\RNr=\RNr[1]</latex>
            </math>: The set of all <subordinate>
               <hot>
                  <math>
                     <latex>1</latex>
                  </math>-tuples</hot>
               <info>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>i.e. a single number <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math> between brackets: <math>
                           <latex>(x)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </info>
            </subordinate> forms a line on which one point has been designated to be <math>
               <latex>0</latex>
            </math>, and a unit of measurement has been chosen. – It is customary to call the line the <math>
               <latex>x</latex>
            </math>-<strong>axis</strong>.
		</para.body>
      </para>
      <para align="center">
         <para.body>
            <media xmlns="" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/R1_illstrtn.gif"/>
            </media>
         </para.body>
      </para>
      <para>
         <para.body>
            <strong>Visualizing</strong>
            <math>
               <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
            </math>: The set of all <subordinate>
               <hot>
                  <math>
                     <latex>2</latex>
                  </math>-tuples or ordered pairs</hot>
               <info>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>i.e. two number <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>y</latex>
                        </math> between brackets: <math>
                           <latex>(x,y)</latex>
                        </math>. Such <math>
                           <latex>2</latex>
                        </math>-tuples are also called <strong>ordered pairs</strong>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </info>
            </subordinate>
			forms a plane on which one point <math>
               <latex>\mathbf{0}</latex>
            </math> has been designated to be the origin, and two perpendicular lines with a unit of measurement have been chosen. – It is customary to draw one of these axes horizontal and call it the <math>
               <latex>x</latex>
            </math>-<strong>axis</strong>. The other line will then appear vertical and will be called the <math>
               <latex>y</latex>
            </math>-<strong>axis</strong>.
		</para.body>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>ordered pair</term>
            <info>
               <para>
                  <para.body>another word for <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math>-tuple; i.e. an expression of the form <math>
                        <latex>(x,y)</latex>
                     </math>, where <math>
                        <latex>x</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>y</latex>
                     </math> are numbers.</para.body>
               </para>
            </info>
         </index.glossary>
      </para>
      <para align="center">
         <para.body>
            <media xmlns="" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/R2_illstrtn.gif"/>
            </media>
         </para.body>
      </para>
      <para>
         <para.body>If we want to give the name <math>
               <latex>P</latex>
            </math> to the point <math>
               <latex>(2,1)</latex>
            </math>
            <subordinate>
               <hot>displayed above</hot>
               <info>
                  <info.caption>Animation of relating ordered pairs to points in the plane</info.caption>
                  <para align="center">
                     <para.body>
                        <media xmlns="" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                           <img src="ims/CrtsnCrdnts2_anm.gif"/>
                        </media>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </info>
            </subordinate>, we write <math>
               <latex>P(2,1)</latex>
            </math> to express that it has coordinates <math>
               <latex>2</latex>
            </math> and <math>
               <latex>1</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
      <para>
         <para.body>
            <strong>Visualizing</strong>
            <math>
               <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
            </math>: The set of all <subordinate>
               <hot>
                  <math>
                     <latex>3</latex>
                  </math>-tuples or ordered triples</hot>
               <info>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>i.e. three numbers <math>
                           <latex>x,y,z</latex>
                        </math> between brackets: <math>
                           <latex>(x,y,z)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </info>
            </subordinate> can be related to points in the world surrounding us. We pick one point, <math>
               <latex>\mathbf{0}</latex>
            </math>, to act as the origin. Then we pick three perpendicular lines with a unit of measurement.. – In the picture below,
		</para.body>
      </para>
      <ul>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>the first coordinate axis points toward you. We call it the <math>
                     <latex>x</latex>
                  </math>-axis.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body> the second coordinate axis goes from left to right. We call the <math>
                     <latex>y</latex>
                  </math>-axis.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>the third coordinate axis has a vertical direction. We call it the <math>
                     <latex>z</latex>
                  </math>-axis</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
      </ul>
      <para align="center">
         <para.body>
            <media xmlns="" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/R3_illstrtn.jpg"/>
            </media>
         </para.body>
      </para>
      <para>
         <para.body>If we want to give the name <math>
               <latex>Q</latex>
            </math> to the point <math>
               <latex>(3,2,2)</latex>
            </math> displayed above, we write <math>
               <latex>Q(3,2,2)</latex>
            </math>. To plot it, consider the box in the picture above. Then, starting from the origin,</para.body>
      </para>
      <ol>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>move 3 units in the <math>
                     <latex>x</latex>
                  </math>-direction (to arrive a the bottom front left corner of the box),</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>from there move 2 units parallel to the <math>
                     <latex>y</latex>
                  </math>-direction (to arrive at the front right bottom corner of the box),</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>from there move 2 units parallel to the <math>
                     <latex>z</latex>
                  </math>-direction (to arrive at the blue corner of the box)</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
      </ol>
      <para>
         <para.body>You can also see an 
			<subordinate>
               <hot>animation</hot>
               <info>
                  <info.caption>Animation of plotting ordered triples in a 3D-coordinate system.</info.caption>
                  <para align="center">
                     <para.body>
                        <media xmlns="" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                           <img src="ims/CrtsnCrdnts3_anm.gif"/>
                        </media>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </info>
            </subordinate>  of this plotting process for several points in <math>
               <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
      <para>
         <para.body>Note that, in <math>
               <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
            </math>,</para.body>
      </para>
      <ol>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>points on the first coordinate axis are given by triples of the form <math>
                     <latex>(x,0,0)</latex>
                  </math>, where <math>
                     <latex>x</latex>
                  </math> is an arbitrary number.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>points on the second coordinate axis are given by triples of the form <math>
                     <latex>(0,y,0)</latex>
                  </math>, where <math>
                     <latex>y</latex>
                  </math> is an arbitrary number.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
         <li>
            <para>
               <para.body>points on the third coordinate axis are given by triples of the form <math>
                     <latex>(0,0,z)</latex>
                  </math>, where <math>
                     <latex>z</latex>
                  </math> is an arbitrary number.</para.body>
            </para>
         </li>
      </ol>
   </body>
</unit>